<HR size="1" color="#dedfdf">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">
After playing for several months on Rallos Zek, I began to realize many of the problems of PVP.  Now first, don’t get me wrong, I LOVE Rallos Zek!  There is nothing like the thrill of imminent death.  I cannot tell you how great the adrenaline rush you feel behind the keyboard when someone smacks you out of the blue.  I have stood over the body of many would be murderers, my hands shaking so hard from the thrill, that I can hardly type.  So let me get on with it.<P>Should players be able to kill other players?  YES!  YES!  YES!  But the real question is SHOULD players kill other players.  In some cases yes, in some, no.  In the case of evil characters killing evil characters, yes.  Evil characters killing good characters, yes.  Good characters kill evil characters, yes.  Good characters killing good characters, no.   What?  Did I say no?  Yes, I said no.<P>But they do.  Good characters kill good characters all the time.  Don’t believe me?  Go to Greater Faydark.  Now the question is, why do good characters kill other good characters?  Because they can!  There are no consequences for player killing except what other characters can do about it, which usually is not much.  Why?  Because player killers are not dumb, they prey on the weak.<P>Now in the Real World, nearly one hundred percent of actions taken by player killers would be considered unacceptable in our society.  Now most of you are saying, this is not the real world, but a game.  Yes it is a game.  A game of a world.  A game of world and the societies in that world.  If you want to kill every player in sight, Doom or Unreal is the game for you.  Even Everquest is the game for you, if you want to play an evil character killing everybody, or a good character killing evil ones.  Now I am not talking about playing a human paladin, worshipping Mithaniel Marr, and you want to say he has gone insane.  That is not really available as a choice in the character generation screen.  So what can Verant do?  What can they do?<P>There has to be a consequence to killing other players.  That consequence should be faction.  Say you are a dark elf worshipping Innoruuk, and you kill a human worshipping Erolissi Marr.  Your Dark Elf and Innoruuk factions should go up, your Human and Erolissi Marr faction should go down.  Now what does that mean to your dark elf?  Well pretty soon you would be KOS in most Human areas of the game, but whose fault is that?  Yours!  Now lets say you are a human worshipping Mithaniel Marr, and you kill a human worshipping Karana.  Your Human, Mithaniel Marr and Karana faction would go down.  What happens when your god’s faction becomes too low?  You level slower, then not at all, until you can quest to amend your ways.<P>I do not think that this would be too hard to implement, and would add to the enjoyment of the game.<P>Sir Rale Dragonsblade<BR>20th Level Paladin - Knight of Truth<BR>Rallos Zek<BR>
</FONT>
