<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">
I agree that a step to control deleveling will help. But will it help enough? I think not. Instead, I would suggest using faction to give return some pleasure to the pvp game. Seems to me the issue at hand is inbalance. Verant takes pains to point out many efforts to "balance" the game. Yet, in pvp, a very serious inbalance exists. There is no down-side to unsportsmanlike, at times just-plain-mean, exploitation of the pvp rules. That is, it costs nothing to kill and steal from other players. At the same time blood-feud and other types of revenge sought by players who embrace the hero aspect of the game, costs dearly. The pvp players, known as pkers, wander freely because they can kill without affecting their status in the world. Antipk players, on the other hand, can not afford to resist the pk players for more than a few hours because they, the antipk players, get nothing for their efforts, no exp, no faction, no rewards. So, for pks, all is upside because they don't seem to care about advancement. When they do advance they merely use their ill-gotten spoils to twink themselves up a level or two. Antipk have only downside because they don't make any honorable advances while chasing unsportsmanlike players. I do not think any effort to address deleveling or cross-teaming will affect this inherent inbalance. Perhaps faction could be used. Killing another player, at the simplest level, could cause negitive faction with every faction group friendly to the killed player. At the complex end, player guilds could be part of pvp faction. This would cause some, though slight, disadvantage for the continual killing of other players. It would also allow players to get friendly/unfriendly messages when conning other players. Just some thoughts.
</FONT>
